  chapel: {
    name: "The Chapel of Forgotten Saints",
    region: "Ground Floor",
    npcIntro: "Before the altar stands a figure of blue-white light in armour of an old fashion, sword point-down, patient as the stone.",
    desc: "A long nave with rows of stone pews facing an altar of black marble. Stained glass windows depict not saints but astronomical events - eclipses, comets, alignments. The glass still holds colour, projecting strange light across the floor. Behind the altar, alcoves hold statues of hooded figures whose features have been deliberately chiseled away. A font of stone holds liquid that might be water.",
    exits: { south: "great_hall", east: "armory" },
    items: [],
    npcs: ["spectral_guardian"],
    firstVisit: "As you enter, the temperature drops sharply. The liquid in the font ripples, though nothing touched it.",
    searchTargets: {
      font: { text: "The liquid is water - and something more than water; your reflection in it stands straighter than you do. A stoppered flask waits on the font's rim, left for pilgrims by hands long gone. You fill it. The font's level does not change.", finds: ["holy_water"], again: "The font holds steady. One flask per pilgrim seems to be the arrangement, and you are not inclined to renegotiate with the last sanctified thing in the building." },
      statues: "The hooded figures' faces were not broken off - they were chiseled away, carefully, stroke by stroke. Devotional work. On the plinth of the third statue, a line survives: 'They gave their names to the walls, that the walls would hold.'",
      windows: "Eclipses, comets, alignments - the stained glass records the sky, not the saints. In the final window, six stars stand in a hexagon around a dark doorway, and one pane at the door's centre has been replaced with plain black glass. Recently. The lead is still bright.",
      pews: "Stone, cold, and worn smooth in exactly two places per seat - knees and forehead. Whatever was worshipped here was prayed to closely. Under the last pew, a child's chalk drawing survives: a door, crowned, and a stick figure holding its hand. Both are smiling.",
    },
  },
